# One Class (or Object) per File; Filename Matches the Type

In the IntelliJ plugin (`plugin/intellij`), each `.kt` file under `src/`
is dedicated to **one** top-level **`class` or `object`**.

## Naming

- **`src/main/kotlin`**: file name **`MyThing.kt`** → exactly one top-level
  **`class MyThing`** or **`object MyThing`** (same PascalCase identifier).
- **`src/test/kotlin`**: file **`MyThingTest.kt`** → top-level **`class MyThingTest`**
  (or the project’s chosen test type name) matching the file name.

## Do

- Split extra top-level classes or objects into **new** files whose names
  match those types.

## Allowed in the same file

- **`companion object`**, nested classes, enum members.
- **Sealed** `class` / `interface` with subclasses in that file; the file
  is named after the **sealed** type (e.g. `Outcome.kt` + `sealed class Outcome`).
- **`private`** top-level helpers (`private fun`, `private const`, etc.) in
  support of the single public top-level type.

## Avoid

- A file named `Foo.kt` whose main top-level type is **`Bar`**.
- Multiple peer top-level `class` / `object` declarations each deserving
  their own name (give each its own file).
